.IX Title "S2P 1"
.TH S2P 1 "perl v5.6.1" "2001-04-20" "Perl Programmers Reference Guide"
.UC
.SH "NAME"
s2p \- Sed to Perl translator
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
\&\fBs2p [options] filename\fR
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
\&\fIs2p\fR takes a sed script specified on the command line (or from
standard input) and produces a comparable \fIperl\fR script on the
standard output.
.Sh "Options"
.IX Subsection "Options"
Options include:
.Ip "\fB\-D<number>\fR" 5
.IX Item "-D<number>"
sets debugging flags.
.Ip "\fB\-n\fR" 5
.IX Item "-n"
specifies that this sed script was always invoked with a \fBsed \-n\fR.
Otherwise a switch parser is prepended to the front of the script.
.Ip "\fB\-p\fR" 5
.IX Item "-p"
specifies that this sed script was never invoked with a \fBsed \-n\fR.
Otherwise a switch parser is prepended to the front of the script.
.Sh "Considerations"
.IX Subsection "Considerations"
The perl script produced looks very sed-ish, and there may very well
be better ways to express what you want to do in perl.  For instance,
s2p does not make any use of the split operator, but you might want
to.
.PP
The perl script you end up with may be either faster or slower than
the original sed script.  If you're only interested in speed you'll
just have to try it both ways.  Of course, if you want to do something
sed doesn't do, you have no choice.  It's often possible to speed up
the perl script by various methods, such as deleting all references to
$\e and chop.
.SH "ENVIRONMENT"
.IX Header "ENVIRONMENT"
s2p uses no environment variables.
